---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro'

const post = {
 title: 'Vector Logo File Setup for Embroidery — How to Prep Your Logo',
 description:
 'Embroidery shops digitize logos from vector files (.ai, .eps, .pdf, .svg). Here\'s why vector matters, what fonts and detail break in stitch, and how to prep your logo so the digitizer doesn\'t have to redraw it.',
 category: 'How-To',
 readTime: '7 min read',
 date: 'May 9, 2026',
 isoDate: '2026-05-09',
 image: '/images/generated/service-embroidery.jpg',
 slug: 'vector-logo-file-setup-for-embroidery',
}

const faqs = [
 { q: 'What file format does an embroidery shop need?', a: 'Vector formats are best — .ai (Adobe Illustrator), .eps, .pdf with vector elements, or .svg. JPG and PNG work but may require redrawing if the image is low-resolution. The key isn\'t the file extension, it\'s whether the artwork is built from mathematical paths (vector) rather than fixed pixels (raster).' },
 { q: 'Why does vector matter for embroidery?', a: 'Vector artwork scales without quality loss. The digitizer can resize your logo to fit chest, sleeve, or back placements without losing crispness. Raster images (JPG, PNG) become pixelated when scaled up, which forces the digitizer to redraw — adding time, cost, and the risk of subtle differences from your original brand mark.' },
 { q: 'What\'s the difference between AI, EPS, and SVG?', a: 'All three are vector formats. .ai is Adobe Illustrator\'s native format — preserves layers, fonts, and effects. .eps is a universal vector format readable by most design software. .svg is web-native vector. For embroidery, any of the three works. .ai is the cleanest input because the digitizer can edit individual elements directly.' },
 { q: 'Can you embroider from a JPG or PNG?', a: 'Yes, but with caveats. If the JPG/PNG is high-resolution (300+ DPI at intended size), the digitizer can trace it cleanly. If it\'s a low-res web image, expect a redraw fee ($30-100) and minor differences in the final stitch result. Always send the highest-resolution version you have.' },
 { q: 'What logo elements break in embroidery?', a: 'Five common issues: (1) lines under 1mm wide drop out, (2) very small text becomes illegible, (3) gradients don\'t translate to thread (must be approximated), (4) drop shadows and glows don\'t exist as stitches, (5) colors with very subtle shade variations get consolidated into the thread color closest to each. The cleanest embroidery comes from logos designed for embroidery from the start.' },
 { q: 'How do I prep my logo for embroidery?', a: 'Five steps: (1) start with the highest-quality vector file you have, (2) convert text to outlines/curves so font availability isn\'t a factor, (3) simplify fine details that won\'t survive stitch (1mm lines, small text), (4) reduce color count to what reads at the intended size, (5) include a Pantone color reference for thread color matching. Send all of this to the digitizer.' },
 { q: 'How many colors should my embroidered logo have?', a: 'Practical sweet spot is 6-12 colors. Beyond that, embroidery starts losing impact and adding setup time. For chest-logo sizes (3-3.5 inches wide), 4-6 colors usually delivers the cleanest result. For larger placements, more colors work. Avoid logos with subtle gradient blends — they don\'t translate to thread.' },
 { q: 'What size should my embroidered logo be?', a: 'A standard left-chest logo is 3-3.5 inches wide × 1.5-2 inches tall. Hat front-panel logos are 2.5-3 inches wide. Sleeve hits run 2-3 inches. Back-yoke logos can run 10-12 inches wide. The digitizer adjusts stitch density based on size — bigger logos use more stitches and take longer per piece.' },
]

